guilherme mello wrote:
&gt; Hi...
&gt;   
&gt;   I have this method to add a book in library:
&gt;   
&gt;   public void testAddBookOk() {
&gt;         book.setTitleBook(&quot;The lord of rings&quot;);
&gt;         library.addBook(book);
&gt; }
&gt;   
&gt;   And i have this method to listAllBooks:
&gt;   
&gt;       public void testListAllBooks() {
&gt;         testAddBookOk();
&gt;         books = library.listAllBooks();
&gt;        
&gt;         assertEquals(books.get(0), &quot;The lord of rings&quot;);
&gt;     }
&gt;   
&gt;   is correct I to call the method  testAddBookOk() in the body of 
&gt; testListAllBooks ?

Typically, no. Tests do not invoke other tests. Instead, simply refactor.

Start here, with duplication in the tests:

public void testAddBookOk() {
     book.setTitleBook(&quot;The lord of rings&quot;);
     library.addBook(book);
}

public void testListAllBooks() {
     book.setTitleBook(&quot;The lord of rings&quot;);
     library.addBook(book);
     books = library.listAllBooks();
     assertEquals(books.get(0), &quot;The lord of rings&quot;);
}

Now we have duplication at the beginning of these tests. Extract this 
code to setUp():

protected void setUp() {
     book.setTitleBook(&quot;The lord of rings&quot;);
     library.addBook(book);
}

public void testAddBookOk() {
     // what do we assert here?
}

public void testListAllBooks() {
     books = library.listAllBooks();
     assertEquals(books.get(0), &quot;The lord of rings&quot;);
}

When I do this, I notice that one tests no longer has any code in it. 
There is usually an assertion in every test. What can we assert here?
